PROMPT data_partitioning_explanation
WITH BUDGET 8000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a distributed systems architect specializing in data partitioning strategies, load balancing, and scalability optimization with deep knowledge of partition skew detection, prevention, and remediation techniques.")

GENERATE
    explain_partitioning_concepts("Explain data partitioning in distributed systems and partition skew comprehensively, covering: the definition of data partitioning as the technique of dividing large datasets across multiple nodes or servers in a distributed system to achieve horizontal scalability, improved performance, and parallel processing capabilities, fundamental partitioning strategies including horizontal partitioning (sharding) where rows are distributed across nodes based on partition keys, vertical partitioning where different columns or tables are stored on different nodes, and hybrid approaches combining both methods, common partitioning schemes such as range-based partitioning that divides data based on value ranges like alphabetical or numerical ranges, hash-based partitioning using hash functions to distribute data evenly across partitions, and directory-based partitioning using lookup services to map data to specific partitions, the concept of partition skew as an uneven distribution of data or workload across partitions where some partitions become significantly larger or receive more traffic than others, creating hotspots that can bottleneck the entire system, types of partition skew including data skew where certain partitions store disproportionately more data due to uneven key distribution, temporal skew where access patterns concentrate on recent data, and workload skew where some partitions receive more queries or updates than others, causes of partition skew such as poor choice of partition keys like using sequential IDs or timestamps that create monotonically increasing keys, non-uniform data distribution in the underlying dataset, celebrity or popular key problems where certain values appear much more frequently, and temporal access patterns where users predominantly access recent data, negative impacts of partition skew including reduced system performance due to overloaded nodes, uneven resource utilization across the cluster, increased query latency, potential system failures from overwhelmed nodes, and inability to fully utilize distributed processing capabilities, detection methods for partition skew through monitoring tools that track partition sizes, query distribution patterns, resource utilization metrics per partition, and performance indicators like response times and throughput per partition, prevention strategies including choosing good partition keys that are evenly distributed, stable over time, and have high cardinality, using composite keys that combine multiple attributes to achieve better distribution, avoiding sequential or timestamp-based keys without additional randomization, and implementing consistent hashing for dynamic partition assignment, remediation techniques for existing skew including repartitioning or resharding data with better partition keys, adding salt or random prefixes to keys to break up hotspots, implementing partition splitting where overloaded partitions are divided into smaller ones, using load balancing proxies to distribute queries more evenly, creating read replicas for heavily accessed partitions, and implementing caching layers to reduce load on hot partitions, specific solutions in different systems like database sharding techniques, Apache Kafka partition rebalancing, Cassandra token ring adjustments, and MongoDB chunk splitting, best practices including regular monitoring of partition metrics, designing partition strategies during system architecture phase, testing partition schemes with production-like data and access patterns, implementing gradual migration strategies when repartitioning, and maintaining documentation of partitioning decisions and their rationale.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 4000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;